MISSISSIPPI VALLEY TRUST COMPANY
A. O. WILSON,
VICE PRESIDENT
ST. LOUIS
June 17, 1935
Harold
M. Bixby,
0% China Atrways Federal, Ino., U. S. A.,
51 Canton Road,
Shanghai, China.
Dear Harold:
For days and days, I have been endeavoring to find time
to write you a line, but it has just seemed impossible for me
to do so.
Now,
there is a definite reason for a letter, and it will go forward at once. The
purpose of this letter is to tell
you first about theapproaching visit in your
city of one of your long time friends,
but there is much more than "one" in the
party•
I refer to F. A.
Sudholt, formerly an official of the
International Shoe
Company, who, together with his children and grand children, will arrive in
Shanghai
on or about July 28th.
They are passengers on the President Grant which
sails fron Seattle on June 22nd, and they will be in Shanghai on the going trip
and also when they return from Hongkong on August 12th•
The Sudholts are accompanied by Mr. and Mrs. Brickenkamp
and family. Mr.
Brickenkamp is President of the Lindell Trust Company and related
to
the Sudholts.
Mr. Sudholt retired from active business some time ago and now
he is enjoying the money he had accumulated.
I think it is fine for him to do
so much for his fanily along the line of traveling and adventure, especially.
Harold, I just hope that you and Debbie and your fine family
are all well
and happy, and, of
course,
that includes Mrs. Case.
I hope she will
stay over there as long as she can and have a good visit with all of you.
know that you and Debbie and the children are very happy to have here with you.
According to the public press, Dr.Holt and wife are back in
this country.
I was glad to learn from your letter of some time ago that you
actually had been going to church out there in Shanghai•
Possibly, Dr.
Holt had
something to do with that.
I am sure you enjoyed your visit with him.
I am always
assuming
that you have, through the Associated Press,
the facts with reference to
happenings back home; so I will not undertake to inform you along general lines.
Suffice it to say that we really do not know from day to day just what might happen,
although we have recovered considerably from the Supreme Court N. R. A. decision,
and really we do believe that we are moving along now in a fairly comfortable
way, so far as general
business is concerned.
The unemployment problem continues
be our great menace.
It is quite evident that for a long
time to come, we
will find it necessary to continue a relief program of one kind or another.
No
doubt,
that is the situation all over the world, but you and I did not think it
would ever come to pass in this country.
With sincerest good wishes for all of you, I am,
Yours very truly,
A Orville Wilcon
AOW: EJ
Vice President.
